
Interview Questions

1) What is a Garbage Collector in Java?
-->The Garbage Collector (GC) is a JVM component that automatically frees memory by removing objects that are no longer reachable or used by the program.

Advantages:

Automatic memory management.
Prevents memory leaks.
Reduces programmer effort.



2) When does an object become eligible for Garbage Collection?
-->An object becomes eligible for Garbage Collection when it is no longer reachable from any live reference.
      
      Examples:
      1. Nullifying Reference
      
          Employee e = new Employee();
          e = null;
          
      2. Reassigning Reference
          Employee e1 = new Employee();
          e1 = new Employee();
      
      The first object becomes eligible for GC.
      
      3. Anonymous Object
      
          new Employee();
          
          No reference is assigned.
      
      4. Island of Isolation
          Objects reference each other but are unreachable from outside references.




3) Can we force Garbage Collection in Java?
-->No.

We can only request the JVM to perform Garbage Collection.

System.gc();

or

Runtime.getRuntime().gc();

The JVM may ignore the request.




4) What is the difference between Garbage Collector and Garbage Collection?
-->Garbage Collection is the overall, high-level process or concept of automatically managing memory by identifying and cleaning up unused objects from the heap.
    Garbage Collector is the specific background program or algorithm (like a worker/mechanism) that actually executes that cleaning process behind the scenes
    It is basically the difference between what is happening and how it gets done.


5) What does System.gc() do?
-->System.gc() requests the JVM to run Garbage Collection.
    System.gc();
        Important:
          It is only a request.
          JVM decides whether to execute GC immediately or later.



